# Information about the Tsallis tool package 

## About

## Installation
In both OS you must be shure the **python3.12** is installed:<br/>
### Windows
Verify your version:<br/>
`py –version`

Install your version through the official website [https://www.python.org/downloads/](https://www.python.org/downloads/), and search for a version equal or over **3.12**.

After that you should be fine installing with the pip comando:<br/>
`pip install Tsallis-package`

Use the version option for install an specific option:<br/>
`pip install Tsallis-package==0.1.1` for installing the version **0.1.1**

### Linux
Verify your version:<br/>
`python3 –version`

Install from the commando line:<br/>
```
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install python3.12
python3 –version
```

## Functions and classes
Inside a python enviroment import the functions from the module **Tsallis_module**, for example:<br/>
```
from Tsallis_module.basic.qMath import qMath as qM
from Tsallis_module.basic.TsallisMaths import TsallisMaths as TM
```
The basic structure of the module is: <br/>

├───basic<br/>
│___│___qMath.py<br/>
│___│___TsallisMath.py<br/>
│<br/>
└───statistics<br/>
____│___qStatistics.py<br/>
____│___TsallisStatistics.py<br/>

The modules can be accessed using **.** as usual in [python importing](https://docs.python.org/3/reference/import.html).

### Functions
`qexp(x=0.0, q=1.0, type=1) -> float64`<br/>
This functions calculates the q-exponential value of **x**:<br/>
&emsp;_x_ is a float64 value or list.<br/>
&emsp;_q_ is a float64 which is the Tsallis deformation parameter.<br/>
&emsp;_type_ is the Tsallis distribution type. For now only takes integer values 1 or 2.<br/><br/>

`qlog(x=1.0, q=1.0, type=1) -> float64`<br/>
This functions calculates the q-logarithm value of **x**:<br/>
&emsp;_x_ is a float64 value or list.<br/>
&emsp;_q_ is a float64 which is the Tsallis deformation parameter.<br/>
&emsp;_type_ is the Tsallis distribution type. For now only takes integer values 1 or 2.<br/><br/>

`qX(x=0.0, q=1.0, type=1) -> float64`<br/>
This functions calculates the q-deformed value of **x** following the Kaniadakis mathematical tools:<br/>
&emsp;_x_ is a float64 value or list.<br/>
&emsp;_q_ is a float64 which is the Tsallis deformation parameter.<br/>
&emsp;_type_ is the Tsallis distribution type. For now only takes integer values 1 or 2.<br/><br/>

After that you should be fine installing with the pip comando:
`pip install Tsallis-package`

Use the version option for installing an specific option:
`pip install Tsallis-package==0.1.1` for installing the version **0.1.1**





